      {
        "id": "3854370231770991312",
        "type": "Video",
        "shortCode": "DV9eU3xjMrQ",
        "caption": "People often change more after travel than after therapy.\n\nNot because therapy doesn’t work -- it does. But environment rewires identity faster than information does.\n\nWhen you travel, your brain is forced into novelty mode.\n\nNew sounds.\nNew language.\nNew food.\nNew rules.\nNew social cues.\n\nYour brain can’t rely on autopilot anymore.\n\nNovelty activates learning systems in the brain.\nLearning reshapes neural pathways.\n\nSuddenly you’re adapting, observing, recalibrating.\n\nAnd something subtle but powerful happens: In a new country, no one knows who you used to be.\n\nYou’re not the anxious one.\nNot the quiet one.\nNot the version people expect.\n\nYou become a blank page in a new environment.\n\nAnd sometimes that’s exactly what the brain needs to rewrite identity.",
